review_blob:
Draft at some random Irish pub somewhere in North South Boston. Despite being served in a frozen glass it's got an orange tint and an inch of white foam though it's hard to estimate how much the bartender poured down the drain to get there. Solid leafy pine notes on the nose. Solid pine on the tongue. Finished clean. Not my fave but bumping my score up some to compensate for the suboptimal conditions. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at some Irish Pub inside the Boston Westin waterfront. Despite being served in a frozen glass it's still golden with a nice piney nose. Big pine on the tongue. Finished clean. Goes nicely with the fish and chips. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at row 34. Pours black with a thin khaki head. Lots of lacing in the glass. Decent roast notes along with nice chocolate on the nose. Lots of coffee and chocolate on the tongue. A fair amount of bitterness on the finish to keep things interesting. Hides it's booze well. Another awesome Omnipollo beer. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at Row 34. Pours black with a thin khaki head. Leaves a fair amount of lacing in the glass. Solid roasted malt notes on the nose. A fair amount of hazelnut and bitter chocolate on the tongue. Hides it's booze well. Nice but I'm not sure it's an improvement of Biscotti Break. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at Row 34. Pours black with a thin khaki head. Leaves a fair amount of lacing in the glass. Solid roasted malt notes on the nose. Nice hop notes on the tongue. If this were served on nitro perhaps more of the oyster presence could be felt. Still it's a pretty good stout. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Birra del Borgo Perle ai Porci (Pearls for Pigs)

review_blob:
Draft at the Pastoral. Pours golden with a thin white head. Doesn't leave much lacing in the glass. Nice floral notes on the nose. Solid salty tartness on the tongue which pairs and blends nicely with the floral notes. Finish lingers a bit. Nice gose. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at The Pastoral. Pours yellow with no head. Slight Apple notes on the nose. Tends towards the sweeter end but not so sweet as it becomes cloying. Finished cleanly. Solid cider. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at Pastoral bar. Pours golden with an inch of white foam. Kind of fruity in the nose with some nice funky hop notes as well. Fairly funky and hoppy on the tongue. Finished clean. It's a nice beer. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from Whole Foods Danbury. Pours black with a thin khaki head. thick and sludgy on the tongue. Leaves a fair amount of lacing in the glass. Solid chocolate notes on the nose. Fairly big chocolate on the tongue but not getting a ton of the lactose or the orange notes. Hides its booze well. Its solid but doesnt feel particularly complex which is probably why it was selling for $8.95 a bomber.

Bottle from Wegman's Fairfax. Pours black with a thin khaki head. Leaves trace lacing in the glass. Big booze and bourbon on the nose. Coffee's there on the tongue but it fades quickly. Lots of chocolate roast and bourbon on the tongue. Boozy on the finish. It's a big beer and mostly successful. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from Wegman's Fairfax. Pours black with an inch of khaki head. Leaves some lacing in the glass. Big booze and chocolate on the nose. I'm getting some of raspberry on the tongue along with the bourbon and the roasted malt. I'm getting the vanilla beans on the finish. Fairly nice for style especially the way it hides it's booze. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Hardywood Bourbon Barrel Raspberry Stout With Vanilla Beans

review_blob:
Bottle. Pours golden with a thin white head. Leaves trace lacing in the glass. Has some red wine notes on the tongue. The taste combines a bit of red wine essence with that Belgian yeast thing. Finished clean. Solid for style. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from Culinaria. Pours yellow with a thin white head. Has some notes of tartness on the nose. Lovely floral hop notes on the tongue with a hint of the brett.. Finishes clean. Its a sour but its also done a good job of being an IPA. Nice.

Draft at Bailey's Range. As the bartender poured she described it as "booze on booze on booze" pours brown with no real head. Doesn't leave much lacing. Nice whiskey barrel on the nose. Lots of whiskey on the tongue along with the spiciness of the rye. Finished clean. Hides it's booze really well. Quite lovely. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at Baileys range. Pours dark brown with a thin khaki head. Doesn't leave much lacing in the glass. Lovely molasses notes and that Belgian yeast thing on the nose. Rich and robust on the tongue. Finished clean. Nice!

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at Baileys range. Pours golden with a white head. Leaves trace lacing in the glass. Slight leafy hop notes on the nose. Very bitter on the tongue. It's like biting into a toasted pinecone. Not pleasant at all. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at Bailey's range. Pours golden with a thin white head. Leaves some lacing in the glass. Not a lot on the nose. Nice grass hop notes on the tongue. Finishes clean. Solid example of style. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle from Culinaria. Pours Black with a thin khaki head. Has a small amount of lacing in the glass. Big coffee notes on the nose along with some roasted malt. Lots of coffee on the tongue. Finishes Clean. Its tasty but I think it would work better as a sweet stout.

Bottle from Culinaria. Pours Black with a thin khaki head. Leaves some lacing in the glass. Huge chocolate notes on the nose along with the essence of peanuts. Lots of chocolate on the tongue along with sweetness from the lactose. The peanuts are there as well. Finishes clean. Nice example of style.

Bottle from Culinaria. Pours almost white with no head. Lots of pepper notes on the nose especially the poblano. Lots of pepper notes on the tongue without a ton of heat which is nice. This is something that works out much better than I thought it would.

Draft at the bridge. Pours black with a thin khaki head. Leaves a lot of lacing in the glass. Not a lot on the nose. Big roasted malt on the nose but I'm only getting slight hints of the peppermint. Finish lingers a bit. Not really feeling this one. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
beer_name: Ballast Point Victory at Sea - Peppermint

review_blob:
Draft at the bridge. Pours black with a thick khaki head. Leaves some lacing in the glass. Solid coffee notes on the nose. Fairly big chocolate on the tongue. Bracing hop qualities on the tongue and on the finish. Hides it's booze fairly well. Solid. 


---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at the bridge. Pours coca-cola brown with a thick khaki head. Leaves trace lacing in the glass. Small coffee notes on the nose. It's served on nitro so there's a slight silky feel on the tongue. A bit of coffee roast on the tongue. Finished clean. Eh!

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at the Bridge. Pours light, light yellow with no head. Slight Apple note on the nose. Slight whisper of mint on the tongue but it's really faint. Finished clean. Eh!

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at the bridge. Pours light green with no head. doesn't leave any lacing in the glass. Faint hints of green tea on the nose. Big green tea on the tongue. Lingers a bit on the finish. It's an interesting beer though I don't know if is ever want another. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at the bridge. Pours golden with no head. Doesn't leave any lacing. Not much on the nose. Slightly tart on the tongue with a slight salt note. Watery. Not feeling this one. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Tap at the Bridge. Pours golden with a white head. Leaves some lacing in the glass. Subtle coffee and chocolate notes on the nose. The coffee's a bit bigger on the tongue than the chocolate but they're both there. Finished clean. This shouldn't work at all but it's so well-balanced that it works brilliantly. Maybe my favorite example of the style. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at the bridge. Pours golden with a white head. Doesn't leave much lacing in the glass. Big, beautiful raspberry notes on the nose. Lovely tartness on the tongue which balances nicely with the sweeter raspberry vibe. Finished clean. One of my favorites of the style. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Draft at the bridge. Pours golden with a white head. Leaves a lot of lacing. Solid wood notes on the nose. Lovely tartness on the tongue combined with an herby floralness. Finished clean. Really nice. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle. Pours black with a thin khaki head. Leaves trace lacing in the glass. Has a bit of roasted malt on the nose. Definitely get the habanero peppers on the tongue but theyre kind of faint. Finishes clean and hides its booze well. Solid for style though I was hoping the peppers were a little bigger.

Bottle. Pours black with a thin khaki head. leaves some lacing in the glass. Big coffee notes on the nose. big roasted malt on the tongue along with the cinnamon and the coffee. Hides its booze well. Is sweet without being cloying, Nice example of style, Definitely a nice way to commemorate number 4000!

Bottle. Pours golden with a massive, pillowy white head. Funky as hell on the nose. I could smell it as soon as I opened it. Very soft on the tongue. Not as funky on the tongue as it is on the nose but its still plenty flavorful. Pretty good example of the style.

Bottle. Pours golden with two inches of thick white foam. Doesnt leave a ton of lacing in the glass. Huge tartness on the nose along with big floral hops. Nice balance on the tongue between prominent funkiness and floral notes. Finishes clean. This is a fucking awesome beer. Definitely belongs in the pantheon for the style.

Bottle. Pours Black with a thin brown head. Doesnt leave a ton of lacing in the glass. Has a lot of roasted malt on the nose. Definitely on the drier side with a fair amount of roast on the tongue.Finishes Clean. Hides its booze well. Its a solid beer but doesnt strike me as an outstanding one.
beer_name: Evil Twin Christmas Eve at a New York City Hotel Room (2011-)

review_blob: Bottle. Pours black with a half inch of khaki foam. leaves a lot of lacing in the glass. Nice smoked notes on the nose. lots of smoke on the tongue along with a solid roasted malt thing. Hides its booze. finished clean. Solid beer.

Bottle. Pours golden with a thin white head. Leaves some lacing in the glass. A bit of grass on the nose. A bit of floral on the tongue. Finished clean. Solid but Im not understanding the massive ratings for this one.
Bottle. Pours light brown with a thin white head. a bit floral on the nose. Has a bit of hop flavor on the tongue along with a biscuit thing. Finishes clean. Not my favorite example of the style.

Bottle. Pours black with a thin khaki head. Lots of roasted malt notes on the tongue. It tastes kind of like tar which is both interesting and extremely off-putting. Its not my favorite style to be honest so this feels kind of like a best-case scenario for it.

Bottle. Pours brown with a thin khaki head. Nice fruity notes on the nose. Definitely get the grape must as well as the funky saison elements as well. They play together much nicer than I thought they would. Finished clean. This really is a lovely beer, maybe my favorite in the Saranac line.
beer_name: Saranac High Peaks Tramonay Vineyard Saison

review_blob: Bottle. Pours brown with a thin khaki head Not a lot on the nose. Lots of rye on the tongue along with a pine element. Im not sure the two really go that well together. Finish lingers a bit. I agree with the eh!

Bottle. Pours orange with a small white head. not a lot on the nose except for some faint pine needles. A weird combo of sweetness and floral on the tongue with a fairly bitter finish. Not feeling this one.

Bottle from Shawan liquors. Pours golden with a thick white head. lot s of piney, floral hop notes on the nose. Huge floral on the tongue. solid amount of bitterness on the finish. Its flavorful and well balanced. Its certainly the kind of thing youd want after a game.

Bottle from Shawans Liquors. Pours amber with a thin brown head. Has a bit of the Belgian yeast thing on the nose. A little sweet on the tongue and its missing a lot of the Saisons funky barnyard elements. Finishes clean. Eh!

Sampler at brewpub. Pours Coca Cola brown with a thin khaki head. Leaves trace lacing in the glass. Nice roasted malt notes on the nose that almost suggest coffee. Malty on the tongue with a nice clean finish. Good example of style.

Sampler at brewpub. Pours golden with a white head. Leaves some lacing in the glass. Floral notes on the nose. Fairly hop forward on the tongue. Finished with a hint of bitterness. Flavorful but not particularly well balanced.

Sampler at brewpub. Pours golden with a white head. Leaves trace lacing in the glass. Solid clove notes on the nose. Lots of banana and clove with a slight bubblegum thing on the tongue. Finished clean. Good example of style.

Draft at brewpub. Pours golden with a white head. Leaves some lacing in the glass. Not a lot on th nose. Notes of grass and straw on the tongue. Finished clean. Solid beer but not the most exciting version of the style.

Sampler at brewpub. Pours golden with a white head. Leaves a lot of lacing in the glass. Not a lot on the nose. Creamy and smooth on the tongue. Finished clean. A solid gateway beer.
